Recently, cyberattacks on the business world have become more frequent.
Access to data from companies such as JP Morgan, Yahoo, Home Depot, and Target caused them losses of hundreds of millions, and in some cases even billions of dollars.
It doesn't take too many such attacks to damage the global economy.
Nor is the public sector protected from such problems.
From 2012 to 2014, there was a significant data leak at the US Human Resources Department.
Access to data on security checks and fingerprints of 22 million employees was disrupted.
Attempts by hackers sponsored by government agencies to influence election results in a number of countries using stolen data are known.
The last two cases of disclosure of a large amount of data concern the Bundestag, the federal parliament of Germany, and the theft of emails of the Democratic National Committee of the United States.
The cyber threat affects our democratic processes.
The situation is even getting worse.
As computer technology develops, data protection systems become increasingly vulnerable.
A new type of computer technology is also of concern: computing on quantum computers that use the microscopic properties of nature to dramatically increase computing power.
It is so powerful that it can hack many modern encryption systems.
Is the situation so hopeless?
Maybe it's time to pack our vital data and prepare for the imminent digital apocalypse?
I would say, "It's not yet time."
Quantum computers are still in development, and it will take many years before they are put into practice.
More importantly, there are major breakthroughs in encryption.
For me, this is a particularly exciting time in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, when I learned about the new possibility of creating quantum effects that do not exist in nature, I was very inspired.
I was intrigued by the idea of applying the fundamental laws of physics to create more secure encryption.
Today, a number of companies and laboratories around the world, including mine, are working on these technologies to put them into practice.
True.
Now we are preparing to fight quantum using quantum.
So how does it all work?
First, let's take a short tour of the encryption world.
To do this, we need a briefcase, some important documents that we want to send to our friend, James Bond, and a lock to keep everything safe.
Since our information is top secret, we need a special portfolio.
It has a special code deputy: when it is closed, it converts the entire text in documents into random numbers.
You put the documents in the portfolio, close the deputy - at which point all the documents are converted into random numbers - and send the portfolio to James.
While the briefcase is on the way, you call James to report the code.
After receiving the briefcase, he enters the code, the documents are decrypted, and voila - you just sent an encrypted message to James Bond.
(Laughter) A funny example, but it illustrates three important coding elements.
Code - we call it "encryption key."
It's like a password.
Call James to tell him the lock combination code.
This is called "key exchange" -
Guarantee that you will safely receive the encryption key from the right place.
And the deputy who encodes and decodes the document.
This is called a "coding algorithm."
Using a key, it converts text in documents into random numbers.
A good algorithm will encode in such a way that it is very difficult to decrypt a document without a key.
The importance of encryption is that if someone takes possession of a portfolio and breaks it without the help of an encryption key and a coding algorithm, they will still be unable to read its contents.
The information will look like a set of random numbers.
Most security systems rely on a secure method of exchanging keys to transfer the encryption key to the desired location.
However, the rapid development of computing power jeopardizes a number of modern methods of key exchange.
Consider one of the most widely used systems today - RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it was assumed that it would take 40 quadrillion years to hack the 426-bit RSA key.
In 1994, just 17 years later, the code was hacked.
As computers became more powerful, we had to use more complex codes.
Today we usually use 2,048 or 4,096 bits.
As you can see, code creators and hackers are engaged in an ongoing battle, trying to outwit each other.
And when quantum computers appear in the next 10 to 15 years, they will be able to hack even faster the complex mathematics that underpins many modern encryption systems.
A quantum computer is likely to turn our current reliable fortress into a simple house of cards.
We must find a way to defend our fortress.
In recent years, the number of studies in the field of using quantum effects to strengthen cryptoprotection has increased.
Some interesting discoveries were made.
Remember the three main encryption elements: high-quality keys, secure key exchange, and a complex algorithm?
Advances in science and technology put two of these three elements at risk.
First, the keys themselves.
Random numbers are the fundamental building blocks of encryption keys.
But today they are not entirely random.
Today, we are creating encryption keys from random number sequences generated from software, so-called pseudo-random numbers.
In numbers generated by a program or a mathematical formula, one way or another there is a certain pattern.
The less random the numbers are - in scientific terminology: the less entropy they contain - the easier it is to predict them.
Recently, several casinos fell victim to an inventive attack.
Combinations at the output of slot machines were recorded for some time, after which they were analyzed.
This allowed cybercriminals to redesign the pseudo-random number generator that controls the drums.
That, in turn, made it possible to accurately predict the spin of the drums and get a big win.
Encryption keys may also be exposed to similar risks.
A truly random number generator is required for secure encryption.
For many years now, scientists have been looking for the possibility of creating such a generator.
But most attempts today are either not accidental enough, not fast enough, or difficult to repeat.
But the quantum world is based on chance.
So it makes sense to take advantage of this fact.
Devices that can measure quantum effects can also create an endless stream of random numbers at high speed,
Which will prevent all these potential criminals in the casino.
A number of the best universities and companies around the world are engaged in creating generators of truly random numbers.
The first quantum generator created in my company was one by two meters in size and was placed on an optical table.
Later we were able to reduce it to the size of a server box.
Today it is the size of a PCI card connected to a standard computer.
It is the world's fastest generator of truly random numbers.
Its performance is one billion random numbers per second.
Today, it is used to strengthen the security system by cloud providers, banks, and government agencies around the world.
(Applause) But even with such a generator, the second big problem remains unresolved: the threat to secure key exchange.
Modern methods of key exchange are not compatible with a quantum computer.
The quantum solution to this problem is called "quantum key distribution" or QKD, which is based on the fundamental, paradoxical characteristic of quantum mechanics.
The quantum particle changes depending on its observation.
Here is an example of how it works.
Let's go back to exchanging codes for James Bond.
Only this time, instead of calling James with a code message, we will use quantum effects on the laser to create the code and send it to James using conventional optical fiber.
We believe that Dr Nou will try to hack access to data exchange.
Fortunately, his attempts to catch quantum keys along the way will leave fingerprints that James and you can detect.
This will eliminate the intercepted keys.
And the remaining keys can be used for enhanced data protection.
Since such security is based on the fundamental laws of physics, a quantum computer or even any supercomputer of the future will not be able to hack it.
My team and I are working with leading universities, as well as the defence sector, to develop this promising technology into next-generation security.
The Internet of Things heralds an era when 25-30 billion devices will interact, which are projected to appear by 2020.
Trust in the systems that support these devices is vital for the proper functioning of our society in the world of the Internet of Things.
I am ready to argue that quantum technologies can secure this trust, allowing us to take full advantage of the amazing innovations that will enrich our lives.
Thank you.
