The flooding was caused by an increase in the water level in the tributaries of the river in its upper reaches, which led to a rapid increase in the flow of water into the reservoir of the Chinese hydroelectric power station Sangxia / Three Gorges /.
At 14: 00 on July 26, an inflow of 50 thousand cubic meters / s was observed in the reservoir, which is expected to reach its maximum of 60 thousand cubic meters / s in the evening of July 27, the Yangtze River Water Management Committee under the Ministry of Water Management of China reported.
The committee today issued flood warnings in one of the upper reaches of the Yangtze River and overflow of the Sangxia hydroelectric station reservoir.
My job is to help computers make messages about the world around them.
There are many ways to do this, but I like helping computers talk about what they see and understand.
For example, in this picture, a modern computer vision algorithm can recognize that it is a woman and it is a dog.
He can say that the woman is smiling.
He can even say that the dog is unusually cute.
I work on this thinking about how people understand and process data about the world.
What thoughts, memories and stories can such a picture awaken in people.
Everything related to such situations.
You may have seen a similar dog before or spent time also running along the beach, and this in turn evokes thoughts and memories of the past vacation, the time spent on the beach, or the time when you ran somewhere with other dogs.
One of my main principles is to help computers understand what it means to have such an experience, to understand what we share, what we believe and what we feel, because then we will be ready to start involving computer technology in processes that complement our own experience.
If you dig deeper, a few years ago I started helping computers write stories based on a series of images.
And one day, while working, I asked a computer what he thought about going to Australia.
He looked at the pictures and saw the koala.
He didn't know what a koala was, but he said he considered it a curious creature.
Then I shared with him a series of images of burning houses.
He looked at the pictures and said: "Amazing view! Awesome!"
Goosebumps ran down my back.
He looked at a terrible, life-destroying event and thought it was something positive.
I realized that he recognized contrasts, shades of red and yellow and thought that it deserved a positive assessment.
He did it in part because most of the images I gave him were positive.
Because people tend to share positive images when they talk about their experiences.
When was the last time you saw a selfie at a funeral?
I realized that by improving artificial intelligence, task after task, array of data after array, I created huge gaps, holes and gaps in what he could understand.
And in doing that, I encoded every possible kind of prejudice.
Prejudices that reflect a limited vision, limited to a single set of data - gaps that reflect human biases encoded in data, such as bias and stereotypes.
I thought about the evolution of technology that led me to where I ended up - how the first color photos were calibrated on the skin of white women, which means that color photos were not adapted to dark faces.
And the same prejudice, the same gap was observed in the 90s.
And we still have the same gap in information today in how well we can recognize various human faces using facial recognition technology.
I was thinking about the latest research where we tend to limit our thinking to one set of data and one problem.
And in doing so, we created more and more gaps and biases that AI could develop even more.
I realized that we need to think more about what the technologies we are working with today will look like in 5 and 10 years.
Humanity evolves slowly, eventually correcting problems in the interaction between people and the environment.
Artificial intelligence, by contrast, is evolving at an incredible rate.
And that means it's really important to think carefully about it right now - to reflect on our own gaps, our own biases and how it affects the technologies we create and to discuss what modern technologies will mean in the future.
Top managers and scientists around the world are talking about what they think artificial intelligence will be like in the future.
Stephen Hawking warns: "AI can end humanity."
Elon Musk warns that this is one of the greatest existential risks our civilization has ever faced.
Bill Gates wonders: "I don't understand why people aren't concerned."
But these opinions are only part of the story.
Mathematics, models, the fundamental bricks of artificial intelligence are what we call access and what we work with.
We have open source tools for machine learning and intelligence that we are willing to share.
And beyond that, we can share our experience.
Share your knowledge of technology and how it worries us and how it concerns us.
We can discuss what we love.
We can foresee which aspects of technology could eventually become the most useful and which the most problematic.
If we all focus on an open dialogue about AI in the future, it will help create an atmosphere of shared awareness about what AI is now, what it can become, and what we need to do to get the most suitable result for us.
We already see and know all this about the technologies used today.
We use smartphones, digital assistants and robot vacuum cleaners.
Are they evil?
Maybe sometimes.
Are they useful?
Of course.
And they're all different.
And in them you already see a ray of light illuminating our future.
The future begins with what we are creating and building right now.
We are launching a domino effect that will determine the path of AI development.
Right now, we are shaping the AI of the future.
Technologies that immerse us in augmented realities bring past worlds back to life.
Technologies that help people share experiences when they have difficulty communicating.
Technologies based on understanding streaming visual worlds are used for driverless cars.
Technologies based on image understanding and language generation are turning into technologies that help visually impaired people better access the visual world.
But we also see how technology can lead to problems.
Today we have technology that analyzes our innate physical characteristics - such as skin colour or facial features - to determine if we can be criminals or terrorists.
We have technology that analyzes data about us, even data like gender or race, to determine if we can get a loan.
All we see now is just one shot from the evolution of artificial intelligence.
Because where we are now is just a moment of this evolution.
This means that everything we do today will have an impact on our future.
If we want AI to develop to help humans, we must identify the goals and strategies that will set this path now.
I would like to see something that suits people well and combines with our culture and environment.
Technologies that help those of us who suffer from neurological or other diseases to make life equally difficult for everyone.
Technologies that work regardless of your skin color or demographic characteristics.
Today, I am focused on the technologies that will be with us tomorrow and in 10 years.
AI can become anything.
But in this case it is not a self-driving car without a final destination.
We control this machine.
We choose when to accelerate and when to slow down.
We choose when we need to turn.
We choose what the AI of the future will be like.
There are countless things that artificial intelligence can become.
And it will become a lot of things.
And our task today is to find out exactly what we need to invest in AI, so that the results obtained become the best for all of us.
Thank you
(Applause)
