Today I would like to show you how we will do different things in the future.
I believe that soon our buildings and cars will be self-assembling, will reproduce and fix themselves.
So, I am going to show you what I consider to be the current stage of industrial development, and then compare it with some natural systems.
So, at the current stage of industrial development, we have skyscrapers - 2.5 years, from 500,000 to one million parts, quite complex, new amazing technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have amazing vehicles that can take us into space - 5 years, 2.5 million parts.
But on the other hand, if you look at natural systems, we see the proteins of two million species that can gather in 10,000 nanoseconds, or a DNA chain with three billion main pairs that we can copy in about an hour.
So, natural systems, for all their complexity, are extremely effective, far more effective than anything we can build, far more complex than anything we can build.
They are much more energy-efficient.
They are almost never wrong.
And they can recover for a long life.
So, there is something very interesting about natural systems.
And if we can bring that into our man-made environment, our way of creating things will have tremendous potential.
And I think the key is self-assembly.
So, if we want to use self-assembly in our physical environment, I think we need to take into account four key factors.
First, we need to decipher the complexity of what we want to build - our buildings and cars.
And it is necessary to put them into a simple sequence - the basic DNA of construction processes.
Then we need programmable parts that can understand this sequence and use it to curl up or reassemble.
We will need some amount of energy that will enable all of this to be activated and make parts capable of gathering under the program.
And we need some kind of backup error correction system to ensure we successfully build what we want.
I am going to show you several projects that my colleagues from EmIT and I are working on to achieve this self-gathering future.
The first two are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These are projects - large-scale reconfigurable robots - 2.5 and 3.5 meter proteins.
Mechanical electrical devices and sensors are built into them.
You paint what you need to curl up into a sequence of corners - minus 120, minus 120, 0, 0, 120, minus 120 - something like that; a sequence of corners or turns, and you send that sequence by cord.
Each block receives its own message - minus 120. It turns to this angle, checks if everything is correct and transmits information to its neighbor.
And they are brilliant scientists, engineers, designers who worked on this project.
And I think it actually reveals the question: are other scales possible here?
I mean, thousands of dollars, many man-hours to make this 2.5 meter robot.
Can we actually scale up? Can we actually embed robotics in every part?
The next project solves this issue, considers it passive or tries to get modification programmability passively.
But he goes one step further and tries to get a real calculation.
It is based on the most fundamental building block of computing, the logical element of a digital integrated circuit directly in each part.
It's an "I-NOT" element.
You have one tetrahedron - an element that will do all the calculations, and two tetrahedrons for input.
One for the user to enter information is the way you put bricks.
Another for information from the previous laid brick.
And then it displays information in three-dimensional space.
So, this means that the user can start moving the bricks in the right direction.
His calculations are based on what was done before and what you told him to do.
And now it starts to move in three-dimensional space - up or down.
On the left side, [1.1] the input is 0 on the output, moving down.
On the right side, [0.0] input is 1 on the output, which means upward movement.
And what really matters is that our structures now contain drawings of what we want to build.
They contain all the information about what was built.
So, it means that we have some form of self-reproduction.
In this case, I call it self-driving reproduction, because the structures contain clear drawings.
If errors appear, you can replace the part.
All local information is stored so you know how to fix it.
So you can have something that moves and reads information and can transmit it from one part to another.
It is built directly inside, without external control.
The last project I will show you is called Displaced Chains, and this is perhaps the most exciting example of what we have now from passive self-assembling systems.
It combines reconfiguration and programming capabilities and creates a completely passive system.
We are based on a chain of elements.
All the elements are completely identical and shifted.
So every chain or every element wants to turn right or left.
And when you assemble a chain, you essentially program it.
You tell each block where it should turn: right or left.
So when you shake the chain, it collapses into the configuration you programmed - in this case into a spiral, or in this case - two cubes next to each other.
So, in general, you can program any three-dimensional form - or one-dimensional, two-dimensional - from these absolutely passive chains.
So, what does this tell us about the future?
I think it tells us that there are new opportunities for self-assembly, replication, repair in our physical structures, buildings, cars.
New software is possible in these parts.
And from here, you have new possibilities in computing.
We will have spatial computers.
Imagine that our buildings, bridges, cars, all our bricks could make calculations.
It's an amazing parallel and distributed power of cleaning, new design possibilities.
This is incredible potential.
I think that the projects I showed you are just a small step towards the future, if we introduce these new technologies, towards a new self-gathering future.
Thank you.
(Applause)
