It is believed that only sighted people can be driving a car.
Until recently, it was believed that safe and independent driving was an impossible task for the blind.
Hello, I am Denis Hong, and we give the blind freedom and independence by developing cars for the visually impaired.
Before talking about this car for the blind, I will briefly talk about another project I was working on, called the DARPA Urban Challenge.
The project was to create a self-driving robot car.
The driver presses "start" and without his participation the car reaches its destination.
In 2007, our team won half a million dollars, finishing third in this competition.
Around the same time, the National Federation of the Blind, or NSF, tasked the research committee with developing a vehicle that the blind can independently and safely drive.
We decided to try our hand because we thought, "Hey, what's difficult here?
We already have an autonomous car.
Let's put a blind man in it - and it's over, right? "
(Laughter) But we were deeply mistaken.
The NSF wanted to get not just a car that would carry the blind, but a car that the blind could independently drive.
So we had to reject everything and start from scratch.
So, to test this crazy idea, we developed a small prototype of a car buggy to test the feasibility of the project.
And in the summer of 2009, we invited blind youth from all over the country and gave them the opportunity to test this car.
It was an amazing experience.
But the catch is that this car was designed to operate in a strictly controlled environment, namely in a flat, closed car park, where even lanes are restricted by red signal cones.
With this success, we decided to take the next big step and develop a real car that could be driven on real roads.
So, how does that work?
Well, it's a rather complicated system, but let me clarify, perhaps even simplify it.
So, it includes three components.
These include tactile perception, calculation, and non-visual interfaces.
Since the driver sees nothing, the system must perceive the environment and collect information for the driver.
For this purpose, an initial parameter meter is used.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration, like the inner ear of a person.
This information is then transmitted to a GPS device to assess the location of the car.
Two cameras are used to detect traffic on the road
And three laser rangefinders.
Lasers scan the space around the car to detect various objects: an approaching oncoming or overtaking car, any obstacles encountered on the road or around the car.
Then all this huge amount of information is fed into the computer, and the computer performs two stages.
First of all, it is processing this information to get an idea of space: determining traffic lanes on the road, identifying obstacles, and then bringing this information to the driver.
The system is also smart enough to calculate the safest way to drive a car.
So, we can also make recommendations on how to operate the machine.
But the problem is how to convey this information and instructions to a blind person who does not have the quick and accurate response needed to drive?
For this purpose, we have developed a whole range of interface technologies for the blind:
A three-dimensional ping sound system, a vibrating vest, a steering wheel with sound signals, a special prosthetic leg, and even shoes that put pressure on the leg.
But today we will only talk about three types of these special interfaces.
The first interface is called DriveGrip.
They are a pair of gloves with engines on the joints of the fingers, instructing the driver how to steer: direction and angle of rotation.
Another device is SpeedStrip.
Initially, it is a massage chair.
The vibration is used to transmit speed information to the driver, as well as to guide the use of gas pedals and brakes.
So, here you can see how the computer perceives the space around the car. And since the vibration cannot be seen, red LEDs are installed on the driver to demonstrate the process.
This is sensor data, it is transmitted to devices via a computer.
The DriveGrip and SpeedStrip devices are very effective.
But the problem is that these are training prompts.
They don't actually give freedom of governance, do they?
The on-board computer gives the driver commands: "left," "right," "add speed," "stop."
We call him "annoying passenger from the back seat."
That is why we are moving away from training prompts and focusing on informing devices.
An excellent example of this interface is AirPix.
It is a kind of monitor for the blind.
A small panel with many holes through which compressed air comes out, thereby creating images.
A blind person can bring their palm to this panel and "see" lanes on the roadway and obstacles.
The driver can also change the frequency at which the air comes out and possibly the air temperature.
That is, it is an interface for displaying multidimensional data.
So, here you can see the left and right cameras of the car, and how the computer processes and sends this information to the AirPix panel.
Here we demonstrate a simulator, a blind person driving a car using AirPix.
This simulator proved very useful for training blind drivers, as well as for quickly testing ideas for using different types of special interfaces.
This is how this system works briefly.
After all, it is a prototype of a car for the blind, and it will not be released onto the roadway until they are convinced of its absolute safety.
And I sincerely believe that this is quite likely.
Still, will society accept such a radical idea?
How much will car insurance rules change?
On what terms will a driver's license be issued?
Apart from technological challenges, there are so many pitfalls that need to be overcome before this becomes a reality.
Of course, the main goal of this project is to develop a car for the blind.
However, it is possible that the side technologies developed during this project will prove to be an invaluable contribution to our lives.
Our sensors work regardless of the time of day, fog and rain.
We can use these technologies together with new special interfaces to improve the safety of cars for the sighted.
Find their use in everyday household appliances, in educational institutions, in offices.
Just imagine: a teacher in a class writes on a blackboard, and a blind student can see and read what is written using these special interfaces.
It's priceless.
So what I showed you today is just the beginning.
Many thanks.
(Applause)
