More than a hundred Russians returned home from Yerevan on export flights
More than a hundred Russians who could not leave Armenia amid the spread of coronavirus have returned home on export flights.
The press service of the Russian Embassy in Yerevan reported this on Sunday, July 26.
"We are pleased to announce that 106 Russians were able to return home on Yerevan-Rostov-on-Don flights on July 26 ," TASS reports.
The embassy noted that the process of check-in and boarding of passengers was coordinated by diplomats.
A total of 2,822 Russian citizens have been removed from Armenia since the introduction of flight restrictions.
On July 24, Russian Prime Minister Mikhail Mishustin announced the opening of flights with a number of countries from August 1.
Kirilenko shared his memories of playing with Bryant and Jordan in the NBA
The head of the Russian Basketball Federation (RFB) Andrey Kirilenko shared his memories of his games against the legendary Kobe Bryant and Michael Jordan in National Basketball Association (NBA) matches.
I knew Bryant's self-esteem couldn't be hurt by any trash-current, so as not to stimulate his athletic anger.
Kobe had a killer instinct, so on the court I tried to talk to him so that he didn't perceive the game in an aggressive way.
On the court I gave him compliments: "Oh!
Kobe, scored well, great pass!
Listening to my enthusiastic responses, he slightly forgot that it was necessary to pick up the ball once again and score another 3-4 points.
We had a good relationship with Kobi ," - Kirilenko quotes" Evening Moscow ."
He also spoke about his first game against Jordan.
"I took care of him.
For the first three minutes of the match, I ran in full admiration for the legend next to me, which I only saw on TV.
While my goiter breathed with joy, Michael scored a lot of points.
Soon I walked away from the delight, covered his shots a couple of times...
In that game my team won, and Jordan still scored 44 points ," - the head of the RFB added.
Kirilenko spent 12 seasons in the NBA.
He was selected by the Utah Jazz in the 1999 draft at No. 24 overall.
In addition to Utah, for which he spent ten seasons, the Russian forward played for the Minnesota Timberwolves and Brooklyn Nets.
In total, he has 797 matches in which he averaged 11.8 points, made 5.5 rebounds, 2.7 assists and 1.8 block shots.
